Data plots using ggplot2

Exploring the impact of variables expend on verbal, math and total score

ggplot(sat,aes(x=verbal))+geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(sat,aes(x=verbal))+geom_density()

ggplot(sat,aes(x=expend,y=verbal))+geom_point()

ggplot(sat,aes(x=math))+geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(sat,aes(x=math))+geom_density()

ggplot(sat,aes(x=expend,y=math))+geom_point()

ggplot(sat,aes(x=total))+geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(sat,aes(x=total))+geom_density()

ggplot(sat,aes(x=expend,y=total))+geom_point()

Exploring the impact of variables ratio on verbal, math and total score

ggplot(sat,aes(x=ratio,y=verbal))+geom_point()

ggplot(sat,aes(x=ratio,y=math))+geom_point()

ggplot(sat,aes(x=ratio,y=total))+geom_point()

Exploring the impact of variables salary on verbal, math and total score

ggplot(sat,aes(x=salary,y=verbal))+geom_point()

ggplot(sat,aes(x=salary,y=math))+geom_point()

ggplot(sat,aes(x=salary,y=total))+geom_point()

Exploring groups with high total score and low total score. A new factor variable can be created to identify the two different groups.

sat$group<-rep(0,times=length(sat$total))
sat$group[sat$total>950]<-2
sat$group[sat$total<=950]<-1
sat$group<-factor(sat$group)
levels(sat$group)<-c("low", "high")
plot(total ~group, sat)

ggplot(sat,aes(x=salary,y=total))+geom_point(size=1)+facet_grid(~group)

Instead of identifying the groups arbitrarily use a clustering method (kmeans) to set up the groups. We need to declare the new variable as factor

data("sat")
kmeans_sat<-kmeans(sat,2)

Example 2: Francis Galton (GaltonFamilies) data set. This data set is available from the library HistData

pdf("galton.pdf")
data(GaltonFamilies, package="HistData")
plot(childHeight ~ midparentHeight, GaltonFamilies)
lmod <- lm(childHeight ~ midparentHeight, GaltonFamilies)
coef(lmod)
##     (Intercept) midparentHeight 
##      22.6362405       0.6373609
abline(lmod)
(beta <- with(GaltonFamilies, cor(midparentHeight, childHeight) * sd(childHeight) / sd(midparentHeight)))
## [1] 0.6373609
(alpha <- with(GaltonFamilies, mean(childHeight) - beta * mean(midparentHeight)))
## [1] 22.63624
(beta1 <- with(GaltonFamilies, sd(childHeight) / sd(midparentHeight)))
## [1] 1.985858
(alpha1 <- with(GaltonFamilies, mean(childHeight) - beta1 * mean(midparentHeight)))
## [1] -70.68889
abline(alpha1, beta1, lty=2)
